### Correct Hook Usage: Top-Level Calls in React Components and Custom Hooks

Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/reference/rules/rules-of-hooks.md

This snippet demonstrates the correct way to call React Hooks, emphasizing that they must be called at the top level of a function component or a custom Hook. It shows examples of `useState` being used correctly within `Counter` (a function component) and `useWindowWidth` (a custom Hook). Adhering to this rule ensures predictable behavior and proper state management.

```js
function Counter() {
  // ‚úÖ Good: top-level in a function component
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  // ...
}

function useWindowWidth() {
  // ‚úÖ Good: top-level in a custom Hook
  const [width, setWidth] = useState(window.innerWidth);
  // ...
}
```

