### Using React Hooks: Avoid Dynamic Mutation and Higher-Order Hooks in JavaScript

Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/reference/rules/react-calls-components-and-hooks.md

React Hooks should be static and immutable. Avoid creating higher-order Hooks or dynamically mutating them, as this can hinder local reasoning and prevent automatic optimizations. Instead, inline the desired logic into a new, static Hook.

```javascript
function ChatInput() {
  const useDataWithLogging = withLogging(useData); // üî¥ Bad: don't write higher order Hooks
  const data = useDataWithLogging();
}
```

```javascript
function ChatInput() {
  const data = useDataWithLogging(); // ‚úÖ Good: Create a new version of the Hook
}

function useDataWithLogging() {
  // ... Create a new version of the Hook and inline the logic here
}
```

