### Identify Invalid React Hook Usages (JavaScript)

Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/reference/eslint-plugin-react-hooks/lints/rules-of-hooks.md

Illustrates common violations of the Rules of Hooks that can lead to bugs like state mismatches. These patterns include calling hooks conditionally, after early returns, within callbacks or event handlers, wrapping the `use` hook in `try/catch`, or defining hooks at the module level.

```js
// ‚ùå Hook in condition
if (isLoggedIn) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
}

// ‚ùå Hook after early return
if (!data) return <Loading />;
const [processed, setProcessed] = useState(data);

// ‚ùå Hook in callback
<button onClick={() => {
  const [clicked, setClicked] = useState(false);
}}/>

// ‚ùå `use` in try/catch
try {
  const data = use(promise);
} catch (e) {
  // error handling
}

// ‚ùå Hook at module level
const globalState = useState(0); // Outside component
```

--------------------------------

### Implement Valid React Hook Usages (JavaScript)

Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/reference/eslint-plugin-react-hooks/lints/rules-of-hooks.md

Provides examples of correct React hook usage that adhere to the Rules of Hooks. This includes calling hooks unconditionally at the top level of a function component and demonstrating the valid conditional use of the `use` hook.

```js
function Component({ isSpecial, shouldFetch, fetchPromise }) {
  // ‚úÖ Hooks at top level
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  const [name, setName] = useState('');

  if (!isSpecial) {
    return null;
  }

  if (shouldFetch) {
    // ‚úÖ `use` can be conditional
    const data = use(fetchPromise);
    return <div>{data}</div>;
  }

  return <div>{name}: {count}</div>;
}
```

