### Separating Concerns with Multiple React `useEffect` Hooks

Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/lifecycle-of-reactive-effects.md

This example illustrates the best practice of using multiple `useEffect` hooks to manage distinct synchronization processes. One effect handles analytics logging (`logVisit`) when `roomId` changes, while another independently manages the chat room connection. This separation prevents unintended side effects and improves maintainability.

```js
function ChatRoom({ roomId }) {
  useEffect(() => {
    logVisit(roomId);
  }, [roomId]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const connection = createConnection(serverUrl, roomId);
    // ...
  }, [roomId]);
  // ...
}
```

