### Avoid Mutating Hook Arguments After Passing to Hook (Bad Example)

Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/reference/rules/components-and-hooks-must-be-pure.md

Demonstrates the issue of mutating a variable (`icon`) *after* it has been passed as an argument to a hook (`useIconStyle`). If the hook's return value is memoized based on the original `icon` reference, subsequent mutations to `icon` outside the hook will not trigger re-computation, leading to stale results. This highlights the importance of treating hook arguments as immutable.

```js
style = useIconStyle(icon);         // `style` is memoized based on `icon`
icon.enabled = false;               // Bad: ‚ìâ never mutate hook arguments directly
style = useIconStyle(icon);         // previously memoized result is returned
```

--------------------------------

### Avoid Mutating Values After Being Passed to JSX (Bad Example)

Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/reference/rules/components-and-hooks-must-be-pure.md

Illustrates an incorrect practice where an object (`styles`) is mutated *after* it has already been passed as a prop to a JSX element (`<Header styles={styles} />`). React might eagerly evaluate JSX, meaning the `Header` component will receive the original `styles` object. Subsequent mutation of `styles` will not update the `Header`, leading to an outdated UI and breaking local reasoning.

```js
function Page({ colour }) {
  const styles = { colour, size: "large" };
  const header = <Header styles={styles} />;
  styles.size = "small"; // ‚ìâ Bad: styles was already used in the JSX above
  const footer = <Footer styles={styles} />;
  return (
    <>
      {header}
      <Content />
      {footer}
    </>
  );
}
```

