### Correctly Handle Hook Arguments by Copying (Good Example)

Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/reference/rules/components-and-hooks-must-be-pure.md

Illustrates the correct approach to modify an object received as a hook argument. Instead of direct mutation, a new copy of the object (`newIcon`) is created, and modifications are applied to the copy. This preserves immutability and ensures predictable hook behavior, especially with memoization.

```js
function useIconStyle(icon) {
  const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);
  const newIcon = { ...icon }; // ‚úÖ Good: make a copy instead
  if (newIcon.enabled) {
    newIcon.className = computeStyle(newIcon, theme);
  }
  return newIcon;
}
```

